gmd:abstract.gco:CharacterString: EARTHQUAKE_LIQUEFACTION_IN is a point shapefile that shows sites where paleoliquefaction features have been identified in the field by Pat Munson of the Indiana Geological Survey and by archeologists of the Department of Anthropology, Indiana University, Bloomington. The ages of the features, which were determined by radiocarbon dating, dating of associated archaeological artifacts, and flood plain stratigraphy are all within 20,000 years before present.

gmd:purpose.gco:CharacterString: The purpose of EARTHQUAKE_LIQUEFACTION_IN is to provide a GIS layer showing the locations of known paleoliquefaction features in Indiana. Such features were caused by strong-motion earthquakes having energies equivalent to Mb 5.0 or greater.

gmd:measureDescription.gco:CharacterString: According to John Hill, Indiana Geological Survey, the points shown probably represent 85 to 90 percent of all paleoliquefaction features visible in exposures along the streams that were investigated in southern Indiana.
Internal attributes were derived from a preexisting database and are presumed to be accurate.

No records exist regarding the horizontal positional accuracy of this shapefile. It is assumed that UTM coordinates were derived by digitizing points that had been plotted on 1:24,000 scale USGS topographic quadrangle maps.
The vertical positional accuracy was not a factor in the production of this shapefile.

gmd:description.gco:CharacterString: Data from a report by P.J. Munson and C.A. Munson was entered into an Access database.

An Access database was exported as a text file. The text file was imported into an ESRI ArcView View and converted to the shapefile named "EQLIQ." The shapefile was then edited to remove fields such as quadrangle name and county name. The shapefile was converted to an ESRI ArcInfo coverage using the "shapearc" command in ESRI ArcInfo.

The original coverage, EQLIQ, was first reprojected to UTM Zone 16, NAD83. This coverage was then clipped to another coverage, INCLP83, containing the area within the 92 county boundaries for the state of Indiana, which was compiled at a scale of 1:24,000. The resulting coverage was converted to a shapefile named "EARTHQUAKE_LIQUEFACTION_IN."

This metadata was pre-parsed and parsed using CNS (Chew and Spit, v 2.6.1) and MP (Metadata Parser, v 2.7.1) software written by Peter N. Schweitzer (United States Geological Survey). The errors generated by MP were all addressed and corrected, except that no values were assigned to "Abscissa_Resolution" and "Ordinate_Resolution."

An updated shapefile, PALEOLIQUEF_PTS, was provided by John Hill of the IGS. PALEOLIQEF_PTS was reprojected to UTM Zone 16, NAD83. This shapefile was then renamed "EARTHQUAKE_LIQUEFACTION_IN." This version replaces the former version of EARTHQUAKE_LIQUEFACTION_IN that is described in the above process step. The new version contains the following additional attribute fields: Quadrangle, County, Exposure_L, No_dikes, Width_larg, Depth_to_b, Inferred_e, and Site_code. Also, the new version was not clipped to the boundary of Indiana, so that additional points exist along the Wabash River.
Field observations were plotted on 1:24,000 scale topographic quadrangle maps and locations were entered into a database.

gmd:title.gco:CharacterString: Paleoliquefaction Evidence for Recurrent Strong Earthquakes Since 20,000 Years BP in the Wabash Valley Area of Indiana
